snippet.title: Brexit referendum: Investment uncertainty in S. Africa
snippet.description:
Nervousness is growing in South Africa over the Brexit referendum, as the EU is the country's biggest trading bloc. Just last week, South Africa and the rest of the Southern African Development Community signed a partnership agreement with the EU and questions have been raised over their future.

snippet.title: British Public Divided in Reaction to Brexit Vote
snippet.description:
After such a close result in the UK's Brexit referendum, many people on the streets of London were also divided on their reaction to the result. 

Brits voted to leave EU with the final result officially announced at the Manchester Town Hall on Friday morning. The "leave" campaign won with 51.9 percent of the vote. Turnout was high; 72 percent of the more than 46 million registered voters went to the polls. 

Some Londoners said that they supported the decision to leave the EU. 

Paul, a transportation manager, said that he voted to leave. 

"Immigration, get our country back. For our children and future, it will be a better England like it used to be many years ago," he said. 

"I am not too sure, but I think the country was a lot better maybe many years ago before we entered the EU, and maybe we can try and get back to that," said Rochelle, an employee at a public club, who also voted to leave. 

Immigration was a major concern for many who voted to leave. On the other hand, some Londoners said that they believe Britain can only profit from European integration. 

"I wanted to remain," said Georgia, a real estate agent, adding "It is better for the economy. It is better for everyone here, and it is just something that I really think we should have done." 

"Our industry is very closely tied to the fortunes, I think, of the wider economy and the European Union. Also, personally, I just agree with the concept of unity as a continent," said James, another real estate agent. 

Londoners agreed they were uncertain about what the future would bring once their country leaves the EU; some were more optimistic than others. 

"I am just hoping for the best. I am optimistic. So I know there are many members of parliaments that are for this, and I am behind them," said Rochelle. 

"There is so much uncertainty, it is impossible to say how it is actually going to affect us and what it will bring, so I think at the moment it is just quite volatile," said Georgia. 

"As for my own life, a period of uncertainty in terms of employment. I am not entirely sure how our industry will react to this. It is going to be probably a difficult few weeks and months whilst we see what happens in the longer term," said James. 
More on: http://www.cctvplus.com/news/20160625/8025085.shtml#!language=1

snippet.title: Stay safe in your trading before the UK referendum vote.  Key levels to lean against.
snippet.description: he UK referendum is upon us next week.  Will the UK stay "In"  or will they opt "Out".  In either case, traders will be nervous. Liquidity will likely be limited.  Look for extremes BEFORE the event (that means at the beginning of the week - not and hour before the event!)   Lean against them.   IF the extremes are broken, get out.  If you get lucky against risk defining extremes, take your profit and be happy.  This is a week for the professionals and their large clients.  Do not to get bloody in the bar room brawl.

snippet.title: EU Referendum: The UK's Relationship With The EU
snippet.description:
A documentary on the UK's long history with Europe, the EU Referendum and getting personal views from many UK Expats based in Belgium addressing the big issues of the referendum.

This is part of a series being run by a young Brit who lived in Belgium for 19 years and now resides in Cardiff. The aim? To inform and involve other young people in this once-in-a-generation debate from many important and interesting perspectives.

In addition, there are 11 full exclusive, independent interviews in this series: 

EU Referendum #1 | Interview: What Will Happen To The Science & Research Sectors Without The EU Grants? - http://bit.ly/1tAvf8d

EU Referendum #2 | Interview: What Will Happen To The EU Students If Brexit Wins? - http://bit.ly/1USIpWD

EU Referendum #3 | Interview: Brexit Would Be Good For International Students - http://bit.ly/1Py7K3Y

EU Referendum #4 | Interview: Why British Expats In Europe Should Be Given The Vote - http://bit.ly/1tu68Di

snippet.title: EU referendum: welcome to the divided, angry Kingdom | Anywhere but Westminster
snippet.description:
As the big vote approaches and many voices say the EU referendum has whipped up the politics of hate, John Harris and John Domokos go on a five-day road trip from post-industrial Labour towns to rural Tory heartlands. 
Subscribe to The Guardian ► http://is.gd/subscribeguardian
In Birmingham, Leave voters cross racial and cultural divides; in Manchester, students uniformly back Remain; while people in the city’s neglected edgelands want out. And one fact burns through: whatever the result, the UK’s grave social problems look set to deepen

snippet.title: Statement by Christine Lagarde on the U.K. Referendum
snippet.description:
For more interesting videos go to: http://newsplexnow.com/

Ms. Christine Lagarde, Managing Director of the International Monetary Fund (IMF), issued the following statement today:

"We take note of the decision by the people of the United Kingdom. We urge the authorities in the U.K. and Europe to work collaboratively to ensure a smooth transition to a new economic relationship between the U.K. and the EU, including by clarifying the procedures and broad objectives that will guide the process.

"We strongly support commitments of the Bank of England and the ECB to supply liquidity to the banking system and curtail excess financial volatility. We will continue to monitor developments closely and stand ready to support our members as needed."

snippet.title: Brexit-Referendum: Doomsday for the political and economic fate of Europe? Part 3, Statement
snippet.description:
Statement: Prof. Dr. Gabriel Felbermayr, director of the Ifo Center for International Economics and professor for Economics at LMU Munich
On June 23 the British people will vote on whether the UK will be the first country to ever leave the European Union. The UK’s relations with the institutions of the continent have always been difficult. A Brexit now, however would not merely be another episode in this difficult relationship but has the potential to deliver the fatal blow to a continent already brought to its knees by a series of interlocking crises.

Against this backdrop we are pleased to invite you to an event featuring three distinguished speakers. John Peet, political editor at The Economist, Gisela Müller-Brandeck-Boucquet, professor for European Studies and International Relations at the University of Würzburg, and Gabriel Felbermayr, director of the Ifo Center for 
International Economics and professor for Economics at LMU Munich, will discuss the political and economic ramifications of the referendum and the developments that have led to it. The discussion will be chaired by the PDU’s CEO, Benjamin Zeeb.
The Project for Democratic Union will be hosting an event at and together with the BMW Stiftung  Herbert Quandt in Munich.

The Project for Democratic Union (PDU) is a political think-tank which makes the case for a full political union of the Eurozone. We believe in a boldly democratic, unified Europe with a strong civil society and public sphere. Our activities range from running on- and offline campaigns to organising academic projects and
enlisting contributors of all nationalities and professional backgrounds. Managed by a group of dedicated supporters, the PDU is primarily based in Munich and London and is currently engaged in setting up representations in Lisbon, Budapest, Brussels, Athens and elsewhere.
Source: democraticunion.eu
Live recording by interpressmedia, June 16, 2016

snippet.title: Brexit referendum: "In" and "out" camps face off on River Thames
snippet.description:
Representatives of the "In" and "Out" camps of the Brexit referendum confronted each other on boats on the River Thames in London on Wednesday. The leader of the anti-EU UK Independence Party, Nigel Farage, led a small fleet of fishing trawlers from the Kent seaside town of Ramsgate up the river into the capital. It comes as part of their campaign for Britain to take back control of its fishing around the British coast.

snippet.title: Brexit-Referendum: Doomsday for the political and economic fate of Europe? Part 1, Event Opening
snippet.description:
Event Opening with Thomas Leeb, BMW-Stiftung and Benjamin Zeeb, CEO, Project for Democratic Union
On June 23 the British people will vote on whether the UK will be the first country to ever leave the European Union. The UK’s relations with the institutions of the continent have always been difficult. A Brexit now, however would not merely be another episode in this difficult relationship but has the potential to deliver the fatal blow to a continent already brought to its knees by a series of interlocking crises.

Against this backdrop we are pleased to invite you to an event featuring three distinguished speakers. John Peet, political editor at The Economist, Gisela Müller-Brandeck-Boucquet, professor for European Studies and International Relations at the University of Würzburg, and Gabriel Felbermayr, director of the Ifo Center for 
International Economics and professor for Economics at LMU Munich, will discuss the political and economic ramifications of the referendum and the developments that have led to it. The discussion will be chaired by the PDU’s CEO, Benjamin Zeeb.
The Project for Democratic Union will be hosting an event at and together with the BMW Stiftung Herbert Quandt in Munich.
The Project for Democratic Union (PDU) is a political think-tank which makes the case for a full political union of the Eurozone. We believe in a boldly democratic, unified Europe with a strong civil society and public sphere. Our activities range from running on- and offline campaigns to organising academic projects and enlisting contributors of all nationalities and professional backgrounds. Managed by a group of dedicated supporters, the PDU is primarily based in Munich and London and is currently engaged in setting up representations in Lisbon, Budapest, Brussels, Athens and elsewhere.
Source: democraticunion.eu
Live recording by interpressmedia, June 16, 2016

snippet.title: We'd like to stay. What about you? | EU Referendum 2016
snippet.description:
As the Directors of Rufus Leonard we take our responsibilities very seriously. Which is why we want to convince the people of Britain to Remain in Europe.

We have looked at the evidence we could find (as opposed to the half-truths told on both sides of the debate) and decided that it would be in the best interests of the agency if we stayed in the EU.

So we decided to use our skills in creativity and motion to create a film focusing on the positive emotional reasons for remaining in the European Union. 

For more information about our stance in the EU Referendum see our Chief Strategy Officer's blog post here: 
https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/why-we-want-remain-eu-laurence-parkes


And whatever you believe or decide, don't forget to vote. June 23rd!

snippet.title: British Finance minister reassures markets after Brexit vote
snippet.description:
British Finance Minister Chancellor George Osborne has made it clear that the UK is not turning its back on Europe or the rest of the world and that there would be no changes to freedom of trade or movement during the negotiation period as the Uk redefines its relationship with Europe.
He was speaking for the first time since the "brexit referendum" in an attempt to stabilize the markets and the sterling pound

snippet.title: RaW EU Referendum Night Special
snippet.description:
As the polls closed at 10PM on the 23rd June, RaW did a special two hour show until midnight. We discussed the campaign, specific politicians, the polls and the effects of either a remain or exit vote. This show also featured three remain interviews from Sir Vince Cable, Baroness Kramer and Liz Lynne and for leave interviews were David Kurten AM, Roger Helmer MEP and Jacob Rees-Mogg MP. 

Hosted by Henry Riley, panelists included Jack Abbey, Joe Wheatley, Matt Allen, Dan Welsh, Ross Copeland, Jon Fawcett, Sam Keeling and Ben Newsham.

snippet.title: Can we EXIT #BREXIT?  Should we vote again?
snippet.description:
Far too much of the #brexit campaign was based on falsehoods which have only come to light now the vote is over.  It is estimated at least one million people would vote differently now if given the chance, that could be five million in a few weeks.  Write to your MP's and ask them to vote it down, ask Nicola Sturgeon to veto the decisions, demand a 2nd referendum now people know the facts.

Reality Check: Have Leave campaigners changed their minds?
http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-36641390?SThisFB

snippet.title: UK referendum: What happens to the EU in case of a Brexit?
snippet.description:
Subscribe to France 24 now :
http://f24.my/youtubeEN

FRANCE 24 live news stream: all the latest news 24/7
http://f24.my/YTliveEN

It is the EU's second-biggest economy, and one of the Union’s two main military mights. But it is questioning its membership of the group. With just over a week to go until the UK's referendum, a decision that will affect 500 million people, FRANCE 24 looks at what the stakes are for some of the other EU member states. 
Could a UK departure bring the rest of the bloc closer? Might it lead to a new type of EU? Or would it be left both economically and politically poorer? Would a Brexit mean the beginning of the end of the European project?
Presented by Eve Irvine
Produced by Isabelle Romero and Mathilde Bénézet

snippet.title: After the UK referendum, saying ‘we continue anyway’ is not a good enough response
snippet.description:
After the UK referendum, saying ‘we continue anyway’ is not a good enough response

The European Parliament has debated the recent EU summit, and the British referendum on EU membership.

ECR Group leader Syed Kamall has warned that seeing the referendum result as an opportunity to continue with ‘more Europe’ would be a mistake.

He said:

“Winston Churchill once said, “When the eagles are silent, the parrots begin to jabber.”

Thankfully last Tuesday and Wednesday the eagles – the heads of government – spoke. Cooler and calmer heads began to prevail, drowning out the parrots.

While the council does not want to live in limbo forever, it is right that EU leaders say they must respect the treaties and must respect the right of the British government to decide how best to proceed.

In the EU, it is for respective national governments to decide how to best respond to a national referendum.

This is the case even now, where the Netherlands has been given the space to decide its response to its referendum in March.

The treaties are clear. If anyone doesn’t like what the treaties say, blame the authors and the signatories. Who knows one or two of them may be in this chamber today?

Some here are quick to point the finger at others and accuse them of breaching the rule of law, while at the same time casting aside our own rules and precedents when it doesn’t suit the majority. Ganging up on political groups they don’t agree with to deny them committee positions or reports that they are entitled to under the De Hondt system. Interfering in the internal affairs of member states where they don’t like the democratically elected government of that country.

The more Commissioners, European parliamentarians and national leaders try to pressure the UK, the more they justify the decision the British people have taken.

The British referendum was just the latest wake-up call for the EU. And many rightly respond by calling for more reform.

The problem is … it is not the reform that Mark Rutte speaks of when he says:

“European where necessary, national where possible.”

Instead they seek to pursue the 1950s European Project to build a United States of Europe, and ask why it has not happened already?

Donald Tusk was right to say that people are disillusioned with grand utopian visions of the future and just want us to cope better with the present.

Some in Brussels draw different conclusions and instead of wanting to get on with a friendly relationship with the UK they seek to foster hope that maybe a part of the current United Kingdom can remain in the EU, rolling out the red carpet for the first minister of Scotland.

I am sure that the peoples of Flanders, Catalonia and the Basque country will be encouraged to see EU leaders enthusiastically embracing regional self-determination.

In this Chamber we rightly talk about the lessons of history. But what about the lessons that warn of the peril when leaders become disconnected from their people?

And increasingly decisions in the EU are not being made in an open and transparent way – especially in this Chamber. Decisions are not always made by all 751 MEPs from across the Continent. Politics is about perception and there is an increasing perception that they are being made by 5 men, 4 of them from virtually the same place in old Europe, sitting in a room and carving up the continent between them. That is not democracy, and if you really want to show that you are open and transparent, stop the grand coalition backroom stitch-ups.

My group does not want the EU to break up, but to avoid this, the EU must seriously change how it works.

Whatever the challenge, more Europe is not always the answer.

Ignoring the results of national elections and referenda and saying ‘we continue anyway’ is not a good enough response.

EU Heads of State and Government are rightly meeting in Bratislava this September to ask some tough questions.

And that is what the ECR Group was created to do. To sometimes ask those tough questions that people in this chamber do not want to hear.

With or without the UK, there are a growing number of people across the European Union who want change.

So my plea to you all is ..

Listen to those who want the EU to meet the challenges of the future
Listen to those who want politicians to start addressing their concerns, even where we may disagree; and
Listen to those who want their leaders to focus on creating jobs rather than creating political utopias.”

Interfering in the internal affairs of member states where they don’t like the democratically elected government of that country.

The more Commissioners, European parliamentarians and national leaders try to pressure the UK, the more they justify the decision the British people have taken.

The British referendum was just the latest wake-up call for the EU. And many rightly respond by calling for more reform.

The problem is … it is not the reform that Mark Rutte speaks of when he says:

“European where necessary, national where possible.”

Instead they seek to pursue the 1950s European Project to build a United States of Europe, and ask why it has not happened already?

Donald Tusk was right to say that people are disillusioned with grand utopian visions of the future and just want us to cope better with the present.

Some in Brussels draw different conclusions and instead of wanting to get on with a friendly relationship with the UK they seek to foster hope that maybe a part of the current United Kingdom can remain in the EU, rolling out the red carpet for the first minister of Scotland.

I am sure that the peoples of Flanders, Catalonia and the Basque country will be encouraged to see EU leaders enthusiastically embracing regional self-determination.

In this Chamber we rightly talk about the lessons of history. But what about the lessons that warn of the peril when leaders become disconnected from their people?

And increasingly decisions in the EU are not being made in an open and transparent way – especially in this Chamber. Decisions are not always made by all 751 MEPs from across the Continent. Politics is about perception and there is an increasing perception that they are being made by 5 men, 4 of them from virtually the same place in old Europe, sitting in a room and carving up the continent between them. That is not democracy, and if you really want to show that you are open and transparent, stop the grand coalition backroom stitch-ups.

My group does not want the EU to break up, but to avoid this, the EU must seriously change how it works.

Whatever the challenge, more Europe is not always the answer.

Ignoring the results of national elections and referenda and saying ‘we continue anyway’ is not a good enough response.

EU Heads of State and Government are rightly meeting in Bratislava this September to ask some tough questions.

And that is what the ECR Group was created to do. To sometimes ask those tough questions that people in this chamber do not want to hear.

With or without the UK, there are a growing number of people across the European Union who want change.

So my plea to you all is ..

Listen to those who want the EU to meet the challenges of the future
Listen to those who want politicians to start addressing their concerns, even where we may disagree; and
Listen to those who want their leaders to focus on creating jobs rather than creating political utopias.”

snippet.title: Brexit Referendum Changes British Political Landscape: UKIP Leader
snippet.description:
The Brexit referendum has changed the landscape of British politics no matter the results, the UK Independence Party (UKIP) leader Nigel Farage said Thursday night at a meeting of the Leave EU campaign. 

Millions of Britons went to about 41,000 polling stations on Thursday to cast their ballots in the European Union (EU) referendum on whether their country should remain in or leave the European bloc. 

"Tonight, whatever the result, is not one for recriminations, but for celebration of the landscape of British politics, in the course of the last few weeks, has changed, and it has changed forever. We'd all lose this battle tonight, [but] we will win this war, we will get our country back, we will get our independence back, and we will get our borders back," said Farage. 

"I promise you this, if the result is that we vote to leave, we must make sure the government carries out the will of the people. If the vote is we haven't quite made it, then we've got a lot to look forward to as continued EU members," he added. 

Though the results of the referendum will not be released until Friday morning, pollster YouGov found that 54 percent of British supported the UK remaining in the EU in a survey it carried out on Wednesday. 

The pollster YouGov also put Remain in the lead, saying that its online survey showed a 54-46 margin of victory. 

Anti-EU campaigner Kate Hoey said that if the UK has decided to remain in the EU, Prime Minister David Cameron should keep his words to push for further reform of the EU. 

"I think whatever happens, if it's a close vote for remain, David Cameron is going to have such pressure within his own party. Well I don't think it's going to be the end of the matter, particularly if it's very close. And of course David Cameron, the prime minister, will have to honor all the promises he has made about what is going to happen if we voted for this so-called 'reform EU,'" she said. 

Richard Tice, a co-founder of the Leave.EU campaign, said the referendum has made the British think about the situation of the European Union. If the Remain camp wins, they should keep the promise to reform the EU. 

"The really good thing is there is going to be a very high turnout, which is great. People who have never previously thought about the European Union, have felt engaged, they have taken an interest. And we on the leave side, if we lose -- it would be very close -- but we will hold the remain camp to account on all the promises that they have made, all the things they have said will not happen," said Tice.

Millions of Britons went to about 41,000 polling stations on Thursday to cast their ballots in the European Union (EU) referendum on whether their country should remain in or leave the European bloc. 

"Tonight, whatever the result, is not one for recriminations, but for celebration of the landscape of British politics, in the course of the last few weeks, has changed, and it has changed forever. We'd all lose this battle tonight, [but] we will win this war, we will get our country back, we will get our independence back, and we will get our borders back," said Farage. 

"I promise you this, if the result is that we vote to leave, we must make sure the government carries out the will of the people. If the vote is we haven't quite made it, then we've got a lot to look forward to as continued EU members," he added. 

Though the results of the referendum will not be released until Friday morning, pollster YouGov found that 54 percent of British supported the UK remaining in the EU in a survey it carried out on Wednesday. 

The pollster YouGov also put Remain in the lead, saying that its online survey showed a 54-46 margin of victory. 

Anti-EU campaigner Kate Hoey said that if the UK has decided to remain in the EU, Prime Minister David Cameron should keep his words to push for further reform of the EU. 

"I think whatever happens, if it's a close vote for remain, David Cameron is going to have such pressure within his own party. Well I don't think it's going to be the end of the matter, particularly if it's very close. And of course David Cameron, the prime minister, will have to honor all the promises he has made about what is going to happen if we voted for this so-called 'reform EU,'" she said. 

Richard Tice, a co-founder of the Leave.EU campaign, said the referendum has made the British think about the situation of the European Union. If the Remain camp wins, they should keep the promise to reform the EU. 

"The really good thing is there is going to be a very high turnout, which is great. People who have never previously thought about the European Union, have felt engaged, they have taken an interest. And we on the leave side, if we lose -- it would be very close -- but we will hold the remain camp to account on all the promises that they have made, all the things they have said will not happen," said Tice.

snippet.title: Brexit: prepare yourselves | Owen Jones talks...
snippet.description:
The European Union is far from perfect but voting to leave in the EU referendum could be a huge mistake. A vote for Brexit could have a number of consequences domestically and at a European level. These could include a power grab by the Conservative right, rising anti-immigrant sentiment and fresh attacks on workers' rights and the NHS. But we may also have to take an economic hit and Europe will be unlikely to want to give us a good deal as it seeks to discourage further disintegration of the union. If we vote leave, we have to be prepared for the consequences.

snippet.title: Man Who Set Up Petition For Second EU Referendum With Three Million Signatures
snippet.description:
The fallout of the Brexit vote has seen chaos at central government, £74bn wiped off the FTSE and the pound falling to a 31-year-low. 

Yet, there is at least one thing to smile about. 

In an amusing twist, the man behind a popular petition to hold a second referendum has been revealed to be a vehement Leave supporter.

The petition, which has more than 3.6million signatures, was set up in May by William Oliver Healey, an activist for the English Democrats.

But, after the shock result, which saw Leave take 52% of the share compared to Remain’s 48%, pro-EU supporters headed to the site in droves.“We the undersigned call upon HM Government to implement a rule that if the remain or leave vote is less than 60% based a turnout less than 75% there should be another referendum,” it reads. 

However, now Healy, in a length Facebook post, has said: “This petition was created at a time (over a month ago) when it was looking unlikely that ‘leave’ were going to win, with the intention of making it harder for 'remain’ to further shackle us to the EU. 

“Due to the result, the petition has been hijacked by the remain campaign. Admittedly, my actions were premature however, my intentions were as stated above. THERE WAS NO GUARANTEE OF A LEAVE VICTORY AT THAT TIME!!”

The poll echoes what Nigel Farage, the leader of UKIP leader, said before the vote, in comments that have come back to haunt him. 

“In a 52-48 referendum this would be unfinished business by a long way. If the remain campaign win two-thirds to one-third that ends it,” he said. 

A YouGov poll on the day of EU Referendum predicted the reverse of the result, with Remain at 52%.

The petition has 3,679,244 signatures at the time of writing.

snippet.title: EUR/USD under pressure ahead of UK referendum
snippet.description:
Yesterday, the two crucial events affected both the euro and US dollar. ECB president Mario Draghi spoke to the European Parliament’s economy committee and US Fed Chair Janet Yellen testified before the US Senate Banking Committee. Their statements caused some gyration in the euro/dollar pair. 
The single European currency was able to put pressure on the weak US dollar for a while.  However, later the euro/dollar pair fell to intraday laws. Today, the pair is trading at the level of 1.1269. Draghi’s comments pushed the euro down as the policymaker noted that the ECB is serious about adopting further stimulus measures. Investors responded immediately.
Currency experts assume that the eurozone’s economy will benefit from the weaker euro. Citing Mr. Draghi, eurozone’s growth is gaining momentum, so the European Central Bank stands ready to act by using all the instruments available. Meanwhile, all global trading floors are marked by high volatility in the run-up to the UK’s referendum. The Britons are due to vote for or against Brexit tomorrow. The odds are the majority are likely to vote for the UK membership in the EU. Such outcome will obviously make a benign impact on the whole eurozone and the single European currency. 
Currency experts do not rule out that the US dollar could fall against the euro in case the UK stays in the EU. Yesterday, traders were encouraged by Janet Yellen’s testimony. However, the US dollar is growing under pressure. The US Fed Chair confirmed the caution approach to tightening monetary policy is still appropriate.
Janet Yellen said that further rate hikes would most likely occur at a slower pace than expected amid mixed readings on economic growth and labor market. The US Fed kept the funds rate on hold at 0.5% at the June policy meeting. 
Besides, the policymaker noted that a possible Brexit vote could shake up global markets. Still the outcome of the UK referendum is on a knife-edge. The latest poll shows that 45% back the remain camp compared to 44% who want to leave.

snippet.title: Africans weigh in on EU referendum
snippet.description: All eyes are on Britain to see whether or not the nation votes to remain part of the European Union. The outcome of the referendum has wide-reaching effects. A Brexit would change trade agreements between Europe and Africa. Analysts say development cooperation will also have to be restructured. The EU is a key donor in Africa, and Britain is the biggest contributor to the EU's development aid budget.

snippet.title: Post-Brexit: Possibility of another referendum?
snippet.description:
브렉시트 이후, 영국 정치권에서 보는 재투표의 가능성은
The political establishment in Britain is in disarray following the leave vote.
But, could there be a degree of remorse among some of the 17 million Brits who voted to withdraw?
A recent petition suggests there could be.
Kim Hyesung takes a look. 
British Prime Minister David Cameron is in Brussels to meet European leaders and discuss the UK's decision to leave the EU.


"Britain will be leaving the European Union but I want that process to be as constructive as possible and I hope the outcome can be as constructive as possible," 

But other European leaders are pressing Britain for a quick exit. 
Ahead of the meeting, President of the European Commission Jean-Claude Juncker said that Britain must make a quick decision on exiting the bloc to avoid prolonged uncertainty.
Angela Merkel, the German Chancellor, also said negotiations can only begin after the UK submits a formal application according to Article 50. 


"We will make sure that the negotiations will not follow the principle of cherry-picking. There has to be and there will be a clear distinction whether a country wants to be a part of the EU family or not."

Meanwhile some political figures in the UK have started arguing for a second vote on the Brexit issue. 

Jeremy Hunt, UK's Health Minister, became the first Conservative politician to show support for another vote on Brexit,... through his op-ed in the Daily Telegraph on Monday.
The minister claimed that the UK should encourage EU nations to reform the rules on free movement for the sake of their survival.
It should seek to have a "Norway plus" option on the table,.. where full access to the single market and control over migration will be granted.
That's why the UK should not invoke Article 50 immediately,... because two years of negotiation before automatic exit is not enough.

The unprecedented situation has had unforseen consequences and caused chaos in the UK's political establishment. 


"The UK itself is in shock. Many people are starting to say "we are not sure what we voted for." ... The UK is now in a situation where they have no leader, the opposition is also facing a leadership threat, so the UK is rudderless."

The matter comes down to one question -- whether the UK will really leave the 28-nation bloc, or will it use the referendum results as political leverage for continent-wide reforms surrounding migration.
Kim Hyesung, Arirang News.

snippet.title: Parlamentsausschuss ermittelt: Online-Petition für zweites Brexit-Referendum offenbar gekapert
snippet.description:
Die Internetseite einer Online-Petition, mit der ein zweites Brexit-Referendum erreicht werden soll, ist offenbar manipuliert worden. Laut Petitionsausschuss des britischen Parlamentes wurden 77.000 elektronische Unterschriften vorerst entfernt - es bestehe der Verdacht, dass diese von Computerprogrammen abgeschickt worden seien.

  We have removed about 77,000 signatures which were added fraudulently. We will continue to monitor for suspicious activity.— Petitions Committee (@HoCpetit…

snippet.title: Britain says NO to the EU machine. Tony Gosling calls Brexit referendum June 23 right
snippet.description:
1943 - Nazi EuropachenWirdshaftGemeinshaft drawn up in Berlin - 
1952 - European Coal and Steel Community formed - 
1958 - Treaty of Rome - European Economic Community EEC, Germany, Italy, France - 
1973 - Edward Heath brings Britain into EEC Common Market - 
1975 - Harold Wilson allows referendum which ratifies that decision to join - 
1990 - Margaret Thatcher refuses to sign over sovereignty and forced out - 
1992 - Maastricht Treaty forms the European Union, EU, signed by circus performer turned arms funding Carlyle group director John Major - 
2015 - Greek national vote to reject Troika & ECB bailout terms is ignored - 
2016 - Britain votes to leave the EU

In desperation she sought an interview with Neil Kinnock, the Commission Vice-President charged with fighting fraud, but she describes how he treated her with "bullying" contempt. At Lord Kinnock's instigation, she was first suspended and consigned to a tiny office without a telephone, then dismissed, finally to face disciplinary proceedings. 
http://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/columnists/christopherbooker/530100 9/A-look-in-the-EUs-unbalanced-books.html 

The European Union is pursuing a similar goal to Hitler in trying to create a powerful superstate, Boris Johnson says.
In a dramatic interview with the Telegraph, he warns that while bureaucrats in Brussels are using “different methods” from the Nazi dictator, they share the aim of unifying Europe under one “authority”.
But the EU’s “disastrous” failures have fuelled tensions between member states and allowed Germany to grow in power, “take over” the Italian economy and “destroy” Greece, he warns.
Napoleon, Hitler, various people tried this out, and it ends tragically. The EU is an attempt to do this by different methods.
Mr Johnson invokes Winston Churchill’s war-time defiance, urging the British people to be “the heroes of Europe” again, set the country free and save the EU from itself by voting to leave in the referendum next month.
The former mayor of London, who is a keen classical scholar, argues that the past 2,000 years of European history have been characterised by repeated attempts to unify Europe under a single government in order to recover the continent’s lost “golden age” under the Romans.
“Napoleon, Hitler, various people tried this out, and it ends tragically,” he says.
“The EU is an attempt to do this by different methods.
http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/05/14/boris-johnson-the-eu-wants-a-superstate-just-as-hitler-did/

A government must trigger the article by officially notifying the EU of its intention to leave. Then there is a two-year period in which the terms of the leaver’s exit are negotiated. During this time Britain would no longer be able to take part in any EU decision-making, and any exit agreements must be approved by all 27 remaining EU nations and the European Parliament. Then after Britain’s formal exit, fresh negotiations can begin on any new trade deals. 

But crucially, there is no timescale or mention of when to trigger Article 50 after a referendum, leaving many politicians worried about a long period of uncertainty.

David Cameron however has hinted that it may be the job of whoever succeeds him to trigger Article 50, and Jan Techau, the director of the Carnegie Europe think tank, says there would be little the other EU nations could do to prevent that.
http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-eu-referendum-leave-article-50-lisbon-treaty-a7100436.html

It’s been a nasty campaign filled with racism & scare-mongering, including the murder of an MP in the lead up to today’s UK referendum on EU membership. Certainly the result will not only effect the EU, but will also affect the UK’s own unity & stability as Nicola Sturgeon says Scottish Independence will once again be brought to the fore if Brexit wins. Polls show an almost evenly-divided electorate. In this edition of the debate, we discuss the effects of a win either way in today’s referendum over whether the UK shall remain or leave the European Union.

"We have to be careful about historical comparisons, but Albert Einstein during the 1930s was denounced by the German authorities for being wrong and his theories were denounced, and one of the reasons of course he was denounced was because he was Jewish.

"They got 100 German scientists in the pay of the government to say that he was wrong and Einstein said: 'Look, if I was wrong, one would have been enough."'
http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/eu-referendum-brexit-economy-latest-live-what-it-means-michael-gove-nazis-remain-leave-a7094931.html

snippet.description:
While addressing the House of Commons on Wednesday, British Prime Minister David Cameron warned of what lies ahead if the UK chooses to leave the European Union on June 23.  Cameron said leaving the EU would negatively affect businesses, and see higher tariffs and taxes placed on products. He added that his government was working to help communities impacted by immigration, but "leaving the single market" was not the way to address concerns over immigration.

snippet.description:
After the UK's decision to leave the EU, some families are worried it could have an impact on them, if they have moved to Britain from other EU countries.
The Leave campaign says that the three million people from other EU countries already living in the UK will be allowed to stay.
But some people are concerned about what leaving the EU will mean for them.
We spoke to children whose parents have moved the the UK from abroad about how they feel.

snippet.title: EU Referendum in the South East
snippet.description: On Monday David Cameron came to Sussex to make the case for Remaining in the EU -- telling his audience in Haywards Heath that a so-called Brexit vote would put the economy at risk. snippet.title: Brexit: David Cameron resigns as UK votes to leave - BBC News
snippet.description:
Prime Minister David Cameron is to step down by October after the UK voted to leave the European Union. Mr Cameron made the announcement in a statement outside Downing Street after the final result was announced. He said he would attempt to "steady the ship" over the coming weeks and months but that "fresh leadership" was needed.
The PM had urged the country to vote Remain, warning of economic and security consequences of an exit, but the UK voted to Leave by 52% to 48%.

snippet.title: Millions Signed A Petition For Another Brexit Referendum
snippet.description:
It seems like some folks in the U.K. are having buyer's remorse over the Brexit. An online petition for a second referendum has gathered more than 2.6 million signatures. It's an impressive show of support, but whether or not it will actually affect anything is another story.  

Even though the vote to break away from the EU won by a simple majority, the petition asks for another referendum if the vote was based on less than a 60 percent majority and turnout was less than 75 percent; 51.9 percent of voters voted to leave the EU, and voter turnout was 72.2 percent.

SEE MORE: The Geopolitics Of The #Brexit

The petition was created in May. And because it preceded the vote, at this point, the petition would affect the vote retroactively, which could make the argument more challenging. 

Since the petition garnered more than 100,000 signatures, Parliament is required to consider it.

This video includes images from Getty Images.

localized.title: Millions Signed A Petition For Another Brexit Referendum
localized.description:
It seems like some folks in the U.K. are having buyer's remorse over the Brexit. An online petition for a second referendum has gathered more than 2.6 million signatures. It's an impressive show of support, but whether or not it will actually affect anything is another story.  

Even though the vote to break away from the EU won by a simple majority, the petition asks for another referendum if the vote was based on less than a 60 percent majority and turnout was less than 75 percent; 51.9 percent of voters voted to leave the EU, and voter turnout was 72.2 percent.

SEE MORE: The Geopolitics Of The #Brexit

The petition was created in May. And because it preceded the vote, at this point, the petition would affect the vote retroactively, which could make the argument more challenging. 

Since the petition garnered more than 100,000 signatures, Parliament is required to consider it.

This video includes images from Getty Images.

snippet.title: FTSE and Sterling Brexit Trading, Deconstruction of the EU Referendum Result
snippet.description:
On Thursday 23rd of June 2016 the people of Britain confounded all expectations by voting to LEAVE the European Union, triggering political pundits in the mainstream media to write reams and reams of gibberish for why Britain voted for Brexit, when the reason why is very simple and self evident in the results themselves! Namely that the people of Britain from right across England and Wales rebelled against the London Westminister elite, and so London along and a few other southern regions were the only ones to vote for REMAIN. 

The people of Britain rebelled against the Westminister elite, rebelled against the bankers and rich who have owned Britain for centuries who were expecting Britain's provincial wage slaves to dutifully vote to REMAIN within the European Union as being in the establishment elites best interests rather than that of the British people who have had to suffer the consequences of likes of out of control immigration as the establishment elite effectively imported millions in cheap slave labour from across eastern and southern europe regardless of the social and infrastructure capacity consequences that I have covered in countless articles and videos over the past year. 

My last video covered highlights of key events during 8 hours of the BBC's coverage of the referendum results night. Whilst in this video I will cover exactly what happened on the financial financial markets, primarily in terms of Sterling and FTSE futures during a very volatile trading session that draws a line under the build up to the vote and its immediate aftermath and which sets the scene of what I expect across a wide range of markets of what to expect next over the coming months and YEARS!

snippet.title: Headline Politics - Mark Carney Responds to Brexit Vote
snippet.description: Mark Carney, the governor of the Bank of England, speaks in London on June 24, 2016, on the outcome of the U.K. referendum on membership in the European Union. 51.9 per cent of referendum participants have voted to leave the EU and global stock markets have plunged in response. Carney offers assurances concerning the strength of the British financial sector, affirms the Bank of England’s willingness to take additional measures to prop up the economy if needed, and outlines the preparations already taken by the bank in anticipation of a possible vote to leave the EU.

snippet.title: Blair Horan -  The UK Referendum Result: What it Means for Ireland
snippet.description:
About the Speech:
On 23 June 2016, the UK electorate will answer the question: “Should the United Kingdom remain a member of the European Union or leave the European Union?”. This panel discussed the implications of the result for Ireland and Northern Ireland in some key areas.


About the Speakers:

John McGrane, Director-General of The British Irish Chamber of Commerce; Blair Horan, former General Secretary of the Civil Public and Services Union (CPSU) and current member of the European Social Fund Committee; Pat Cox former President of the European Parliament; Dan O'Brien Chief Economist at the IIEA; and Brendan Halligan, IIEA Chairman.

snippet.title: Brexit Referendum | Brits Head to the Polls
snippet.description:
Voters in Britain will determine whether their country stays in or leaves the European Union.

Brits will head to the polls on Thursday in a national referendum to weigh in on a question that will drastically impact Europe's future: Should the United Kingdom .

Voters in the United Kingdom head to the polls in just over 24 hours for a referendum on whether they should stay or leave the European Union. A possible exit .

Brits head to the polls today to decide their future. If they choose 'Brexit'-to leave the European Union, supporters say they risk economic and trade disaster.

snippet.title: The EU Referendum & Migrants
snippet.description:
The EU referendum, a situation the media and politicians are getting really excited about without taking the proper precautions.

So we at Scenes of Reason spent a lot of time working out the hypothetical scenarios if we ‘vote leave’. Kalina is on a one woman mission to get the eligable men back to Bulgaria and is debunking all the myths around the Referendum and Migrants...

“It’s taken my friends, the good looking men and left our Bulgarian nightclubs empty for TOO LONG! 

It’s about time we shut gates to this UK. So I researched how my friends keep leaving so I can stop them in future. My plans may be helped if these whining Brits leave European Union. It took lifetime but this is how referendum could affects EU migrants… 

Ok so, because my country’s member of EU, my friends benefit from Free Movement agreement and  they can move to UK easily for work. 

Once there and looking for job they can take this thing called the “habitual residence test”. The test ensures EU migrants have legal right to stay in UK AND that they plan to make it home for a while. If they couldn’t find job after three months they can apply for Jobseeker's allowance.

At the moment, once a job is found EU migrants can apply for Universal Credit like any UK national.

BUT! What will happen to EU migration if UK leaves EU? 

IF THE UK LEAVES

Hypothetically, EEA migrants might still be able to move to UK, but this’d happen if UK allows free movement in exchange for access the single market.

My friends who are already there are unlikely to be forced to leave (damn it).

They say if the UK leaves there will be tighter controls on immigration and because of less people there’ll be less pressure on UK public services. AND they say UK will have better system to stop people who can’t contribute to economy or have criminal background.

IF THE UK REMAINS

British Prime Minister David Cameron’s has tried to slow down numbers with reform like:

EU migrants, who don’t find job within 6 months can be deported...come back my preciouses.

Benefits for working EU migrants will be phased in over their first four years of working there. 

So if UK stays, my mission to stop my friends and potential suitors from moving to UK will most likely fail meaning a life of loneliness for me. 

If UK leaves immigration to UK could be more complicated, with stricter limitations to work in the form of work permits or a points based system. BUT it’ll depend on the deals arranged, so there is still chance for me mwahahahaha.

#TurnUp and vote.”

Vote in the EU Referendum 23rd June
For more info head to https://www.scenesofreason.com
tags: will leaving the eu affect immigration

snippet.title: Gabi Zimmer, DIE LINKE.: Erklärung nach dem Brexit-Referendum
snippet.description:
Gabi Zimmer, Vorsitzende der Linksfraktion GUE/NGL (DIE LINKE.) zum Referendum in Groß-Britannien am 24.06.2016. 

Hier der Text zu ihrer diesbezüglichen Pressemitteilung (englisch): In response to the decision of the United Kingdom to leave the European Union, GUE/NGL President Gabi Zimmer, comments:

"We totally respect the British electorate's democratic rights and wishes. It is now up to Brussels and London to find the best way forward that is fair to both sides during the exit negotiations."

"Regretfully, the United Kingdom decided to leave the European Union. In a campaign based on fear mongering, misinformation and half-truths on both sides, British voters were given a binary choice between an increasingly undemocratic, unaccountable neoliberal agenda of the European Union, or a nostalgic, xenophobic and anti-immigration vision for the UK.

"The UK must assume responsibility for this decision immediately. We do not accept David Cameron's proposal to wait until October for a new Prime Minister to decide when to begin the formal withdrawal negotiations. Today is the day that the people of the UK decided to leave. We will not accept that Cameron plays a dirty game now in order to win time to find ways not to implement the result of the referendum.

"Looking towards our Irish friends and colleagues we hope that the Irish peace process will continue and that UK leaving the EU will not make the process stop or deteriorate.

"We support our Irish colleagues' call for a vote on Irish reunificiation following the UK's departure from the EU.

"The European Union must reflect on Brexit and take a hard look at itself as to why a majority of British voters chose to leave after 43 years and why there is also distrust growing among EU citizens towards the EU.

"The EU is in dire need of progressive reform, and its neoliberal and austerity-driven agenda has not only harmed the soon-to-be 27 member states, but is haemorrhaging support from those struggling for a social EU based on solidarity.

"The problem will only be exacerbated if progressive reform is further delayed. Brexit and the rise of Euroscepticism is a damning indictment that a neoliberal elite has detached itself and the EU institutions from a majority of the population.

"Brexit should serve as a wake-up call to those who care about the European project," Zimmer concludes.

localized.title: Gabi Zimmer, DIE LINKE.: Erklärung nach dem Brexit-Referendum
localized.description:
Gabi Zimmer, Vorsitzende der Linksfraktion GUE/NGL (DIE LINKE.) zum Referendum in Groß-Britannien am 24.06.2016. 

Hier der Text zu ihrer diesbezüglichen Pressemitteilung (englisch): In response to the decision of the United Kingdom to leave the European Union, GUE/NGL President Gabi Zimmer, comments:

"We totally respect the British electorate's democratic rights and wishes. It is now up to Brussels and London to find the best way forward that is fair to both sides during the exit negotiations."

"Regretfully, the United Kingdom decided to leave the European Union. In a campaign based on fear mongering, misinformation and half-truths on both sides, British voters were given a binary choice between an increasingly undemocratic, unaccountable neoliberal agenda of the European Union, or a nostalgic, xenophobic and anti-immigration vision for the UK.

"The UK must assume responsibility for this decision immediately. We do not accept David Cameron's proposal to wait until October for a new Prime Minister to decide when to begin the formal withdrawal negotiations. Today is the day that the people of the UK decided to leave. We will not accept that Cameron plays a dirty game now in order to win time to find ways not to implement the result of the referendum.

snippet.title: easyMarkets - Hot Topic - UK Referendum - Brexit
snippet.description:
25$ No Deposit Trading Bonus  Get It Here:  http://www.easymarkets.com/gtw/6288142.aspx

After months of anticipation the Brexit referendum will finally take place this Thursday. Let’s look at how the markets are reacting

  At the end of Friday’s trading session, the pound increased against the U.S. dollar by 0.48% and was trading at $1.43602.
  On a weekly basis, the cable increased by 1.2%. 
  In relation to the euro, the sterling also rose on Friday by 0.4% and ended trading at €1.27385.
  The euro dropped against the dollar most of last week but saw a sharp rise at the beginning of this one.
  Global equities have been rallying leading up to the vote with the footsie opening the week 2.4% higher.


So what led to the pound’s and stocks rally?
  The latest polls are showing a greater support to ‘remain’ in Europe at 45% with 42% support-ing a ‘leave’ vote.
  The appalling news of the killing British MP Jo Cox might have shifted market forecasts for a “Remain” result 
  Jo Cox was in favour of the UK to stick with its EU membership and her murder may have swayed public opinion in line with her position.

Will it all be doom and gloom if the UK votes to leave?
  Eurozone policymakers remain divided as to what the implications from a potential Brexit could be for the group and its common currency, the euro.
  Dutch finance minister and chairman of Eurozone’s group of finance ministers Jeroen Dijs-selbloem believes that in case of a Brexit, no major monetary policy changes would be required on a Eurozone level. 
  However, a number of others including Finland’s finance minister Alexander Stubb, estimate that Brexit would be followed by a financial crisis similar to the one experienced in 2008
  The IMF have said a Brexit would have a negative effect on the UK’s labour market and a de-crease in wages as well as see fuel prices rise.


We’re in for a busy week for the markets – will it end with a bang or a fizzle? It’s up to the UK pub-lic and the world is watching!

snippet.title: Korean markets in turmoil ahead of UK referendum results
snippet.description:
코스피 '브리메인' 기대감에 2,000선 돌파 출발 + 기재차관 "외환시장 변동성 지나치면 시장안정조치"
Markets here in Korea are also feeling the heat as the results from Britain's EU referendum come flooding in.
The Korean government has called an emergency meeting and pledged to counteract excessive market volatility with measures to stabilize the markets.
Hwang Ji-hye tells us more. 
Korea's benchmark Kospi opened up three-quarters-of-percent higher on Friday morning..., above the two-thousand level,... as investors bet on Britain remaining in the EU.
But with early results from Britain putting the leave camp in the lead,... the index soon lost its earlier gains... trading at around one-thousand-980 as of 11 a.m., local time.
The tech-heavy Kosdaq is also trading down around zero-point-three percent compared to Thursday's close, erasing its gains at trade opening of roughly one percent.
As the results from Britain pour in,... the Korean government said that, if needed,... it will quickly push through measures to stabilize local markets. 

"If local foreign exchange and financial market volatility increases excessively, we will quickly push through market stabilization measures that are necessary in relevant situations."

The government held an emergency meeting with other financial authorities on Friday morning... to gauge the possible impacts of the UK referendum.
The Bank of Korea also plans to join government efforts, while closely monitoring the market until the final results are out. 
Major global institutions like the IMF, however, expect a Brexit to have a limited impact on the real economy of non-European countries, including Korea.
Hwang Ji-hye, Arirang News. 

We are certainly seeing a very jittery market here in Korea...
The Kospi is currently trading at the one-thousand-950 level... down nearly two percent from yesterday's close.
The foreign exchange market is also taking a hit... with the Korean won weakening against the greenback... once hitting one-thousand-160 won to the U.S. dollar.

snippet.title: Pat Cox -  The UK Referendum Result: What it Means for Ireland
snippet.description:
About the Speech:
On 23 June 2016, the UK electorate will answer the question: “Should the United Kingdom remain a member of the European Union or leave the European Union?”. This panel discussed the implications of the result for Ireland and Northern Ireland in some key areas.


About the Speakers:

John McGrane, Director-General of The British Irish Chamber of Commerce; Blair Horan, former General Secretary of the Civil Public and Services Union (CPSU) and current member of the European Social Fund Committee; Pat Cox former President of the European Parliament; Dan O'Brien Chief Economist at the IIEA; and Brendan Halligan, IIEA Chairman.

My vote, I didn’t think was going to matter too much because I thought we were just going to Remain, and the David Cameron resignation has blown me away to be honest.

I think the period of uncertainty that we’re going to have for the next couple of months, that’s just been magnified now.

So yeah, quite worried.

snippet.title: A continent apart? Europe and the Brexit referendum (part 1)
snippet.description:
Subscribe to France 24 now :
http://f24.my/youtubeEN

FRANCE 24 live news stream: all the latest news 24/7
http://f24.my/YTliveEN

It’s a make-or-break week for Europe. The continent awoke to news of an insurgent Eurosceptic party taking Rome and Turin’s city halls, and the week will end with elections in Spain. Britain's in-out referendum campaign has been high stakes, not just for Britain but for the whole continent. Whether it's Remain or Leave, the arguments have already rocked Brussels to the core. What would the European Union look like without Great Britain? What domino effect would a Brexit have on the continent?
Produced by Charles WENTE, François WIBAUX and Van MEGUERDITCHIAN.

snippet.title: The Brexit vote could have consciences on SA and Britain economies: Gordhan
snippet.description:
South African government says it will continue to retain strong trade and financial relations with both Britain and the European Union. 
This after Britain voted on Thursday to leave the EU.
The National Treasury and the South African Reserve Bank said they have been in discussions with financial institutions on the possible implications for the South African economy. President Jacob Zuma has said government will advise the South African public about unfolding developments where necessary around the outcome of the Brexit referendum.

For more news, visit: http://www.sabc.co.za/news

snippet.title: Boris Johnson's HQ as the EU referendum result comes in.
snippet.description:
#brexit #regrexit #notmyvote #EUreferendum #BorisJohnson #referendum #Leave #EU #voteleave #voteremain

EDIT: Apparently some of our overseas friends don't understand some of the references in the video.  Here is a list of links to help :)

Wales votes Leave in spite of massive EU funding:  https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jun/25/view-wales-town-showered-eu-cash-votes-leave-ebbw-vale?CMP=share_btn_fb 

Cornwall votes Leave in spite of receiving huge EU subsidies:  http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/brexit-cornwall-issues-plea-for-funding-protection-after-county-overwhelmingly-votes-in-favour-of-a7101311.html

Some admit they used their Leave vote as a protest, believing it wouldn’t matter; some didn’t realise voting “Leave the EU” would mean leaving the EU; some didn’t think their vote would count as the UK would Remain anyway, etc etc – numerous, including:  http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-anger-bregret-leave-voters-protest-vote-thought-uk-stay-in-eu-remain-win-a7102516.html  
http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3658563/Meet-Bregretters-Public-backed-Leave-vote-say-want-STAY-EU-one-admits-didn-t-think-vote-count.html  
http://metro.co.uk/2016/06/24/man-who-voted-for-leave-says-he-thought-his-vote-wouldnt-count-wins-moron-of-the-year-award-5964450/

Lots of Leave voters now want to change their votes:  http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-eu-referendum-bregret-leave-petition-second-remain-latest-will-we-leave-a7105116.html

Head of UK Statistics Authority rebukes Leave campaign for £350m per week claim (twice):  21st April 2016 https://www.statisticsauthority.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/Letter-from-Sir-Andrew-Dilnot-to-Norman-Lamb-MP-210416.pdf  and 27th May 2016 https://www.statisticsauthority.gov.uk/news/uk-statistics-authority-statement-on-the-use-of-official-statistics-on-contributions-to-the-european-union/  and widespread media coverage e.g. http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/27/uk-statistics-chief-vote-leave-350m-figure-misleading 

Leading experts, including ten nobel-prize winning economists, 5,000 scientists and 1,000 academics appeal to voters urging them to vote to Remain:  http://labourlist.org/2016/06/nobel-laureates-join-new-wave-of-experts-backing-remain/ 
http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/eu-referendum-brexit-supporters-opponents

Michael Gove dismisses “experts”: http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/06/eu-referendum-who-needs-experts-when-weve-got-michael-gove/ 

Channel 4 News - man from Barnsley voted Leave to “stop the Muslims coming into our country”:  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jpnbSZGlhq4 

Adam from Manchester didn’t think his vote would count: http://www.unilad.co.uk/video/this-leave-voters-reaction-to-brexit-proves-were-all-fcked/ 

Petition for re-run of referendum if less than 60% majority (ironically, the petition was started by a Leave campaigner in the expectation they would lose): https://petition.parliament.uk/petitions/131215/

Boris didn’t ever really think Leave would win: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERHfuzyic8M


Hope this helps :)


Make your own Hitler video at http://downfall.jfedor.org/

snippet.title: Boris Johnson and Nicola Sturgeon lock horns in UK referendum debate
snippet.description:
The latest television debate over the UK referendum took place in London on Thursday. The debate televised on ITV featured former London mayor Boris Johnson on the 'Leave' side and 'Remain' politicians including Scottish First Minister Nicola Sturgeon. Both sides have been vocal in suggesting that the other is misleading voters over a number of issues, not least immigration.

snippet.title: Brexit referendum
snippet.description:
A week ahead of the Brexit vote, we weighed in on the latest polls and the potential consequences of an exit from the EU. Why is the race so close? What's driving each side? And are the warnings about economic disaster for a Britain outside the EU exaggerated, as many in the Leave camp believe? If a Brexit does indeed occur, will the UK and EU be able to maintain a positive relationship? Join us for a discussion about these issues as the countdown to the referendum continues. We spoke with Wang Yiwei, Director of the Center for EU Studies at Renmin University; in Southampton, Mike Bastin, Visiting Professor at Beijing's University of International Business and Economics; and in Brussels, Paul Ivan, Policy Analyst at the European Policy Center.

snippet.title: PM There Will Be No Second Vote  : EU Referendum
snippet.description:
David Cameron said, despite what some people may think, there will be no second vote.

UPDATE: 27/06/16 

David Cameron has ruled out a second referendum on Britain’s EU membership.

The Prime Minister’s spokesperson said that holding another vote was “not remotely on the cards”. The clarification comes amid a petition calling for a re-run in the event of a close result and following speculation that the government may go to the country again once the terms of Britain’s new relationship have been agreed. "There was a decisive result [in the EU referendum]. The focus of the Cabinet discussion was how we get on and deliver that.”

snippet.title: U.K. votes in historic 'Brexit' referendum
snippet.description:
LONDON — People in the United Kingdom are voting in an historic referendum on whether to remain part of the European Union on Thursday, a vote whose result will have repercussions around the world.

Much of the debate has focused on whether Britain's economy and the control of immigration would fare better it the U.K. left the 28-member bloc — “Brexit.”

As campaigning for and against Brexit entered its final laps Wednesday, polls showed a virtual dead heat.

If the U.K. votes to sever ties with the alliance, it would be the first sovereign nation to do so. It is the third nationwide referendum the U.K. has held.

Polls opened at 2 a.m. ET (7 a.m. local time) and close at 5 p.m. ET Thursday (10 p.m. local time).

Many in the southeast of England, including London, woke to heavy rain which was forecast to ease before resuming in the afternoon. Forecasters said people in western Scotland, Northern Ireland and northern parts of England could expect some scattered showers throughout the day.

The question on the ballot paper is: "Should the United Kingdom remain a member of the European Union or leave the European Union?" The side that gets more than 50% of the votes will win.

The Electoral Commission said a record 46.5 million people have registered to vote.  The results are expected Friday morning.

snippet.title: Brexit referendum: UK’s Gibraltar faces isolation
snippet.description:
Britain’s vote on whether to stay or leave the European Union could have huge consequences for the whole of Europe. But there are some areas within the EU that could feel the impact of a “Brexit” more than most. Spain ceded Gibraltar to Britain in 1713 under a treaty Spain now disputes. Sovereignty over the peninsula remains unresolved. If Britain votes to leave the EU, many of the 32,000 residents here fear that would boost Spain’s hopes of reclaiming sovereignty, but Gibraltar officials dismiss that possibility.

snippet.title: Brexit Vote: What will happen to the Pound Sterling?
snippet.description:
What could the Brexit Vote Mean for your Investments?  We ask David Morrison, Market Analyst at Spread Co http://www.financial-spread-betting.com/spreadbetting/Spreadco-compare.html
What are the BIG risks?  What will happen to the Pound Sterling?  Will Sterling take a dive.  Brexit Opinion Polls.  
Opinion Polls on UK Referendum.The warnings. 
Which kind of stocks could suffer? 
What will the impact be on YOUR portfolio? 
DOOMSDAY - Will everyone sell? Will companies pack up and leave?
What will happen to the Sterling?  GBP/EUR exchange rate..

We speak to David Morrison about the risks of the United Kingdom leaving the EU and about people voting in the UK referendum.  What will happen to Sterling?  What could the Brexit vote mean for your investments.  The Referendum is a very big deal and it is overhanging the markets with uncertainty.  This is a very binary thing; we are either in or out of the European Union.  The main market that will move on the big day is Sterling and it is thought that the UK Pound could move by up to 20%.

snippet.title: Alternative Futures for the S&P 500 in 2016-Q2 - Brexit Vote Reaction
snippet.description:
Animation of the trajectory of the S&P 500 from 7 April 2016 through 1 July 2016, against the backdrop of the alternative trajectories that our dividend-futures based model projected it might take depending upon how far into the future investors were looking during the second quarter of 2016.  

The video captures the Lévy flight events in the S&P 500's stock prices that were caused by the reaction to the U.K.'s "Brexit" referendum after 23 June 2016 and the response of central banks in the remaining days of 2016-Q2.  See the following post for more information about the onset of the event:

http://politicalcalculations.blogspot.com/2016/06/the-s-500-in-week-4-of-june-2016.html

And the following post for a discussion of the aftermath. 

http://politicalcalculations.blogspot.com/2016/07/the-s-500-in-week-5-of-june-2016.html

snippet.title: Brexit Referendum | Brits Head to the Polls
snippet.description:
Voters in Britain will determine whether their country stays in or leaves the European Union.

Brits will head to the polls on Thursday in a national referendum to weigh in on a question that will drastically impact Europe's future: Should the United Kingdom .

Voters in the United Kingdom head to the polls in just over 24 hours for a referendum on whether they should stay or leave the European Union. A possible exit .

Brits head to the polls today to decide their future. If they choose 'Brexit'-to leave the European Union, supporters say they risk economic and trade disaster.

snippet.description:
The Latest opinion polls taken today (22nd of June) both put LEAVE marginally ahead of REMAIN, TNS (online) 43% LEAVE against 41% for REMAIN and Opinium (online) 45% LEAVE against 44% for REMAIN. Which illustrates that whilst leave as the advantage nevertheless given the margin of error then both camps are virtually neck and neck, literally balanced on a knife edge going into voting day that compares against the dramatic shifts in the poll leads of the past 10 days.

snippet.title: John McGrane -  The UK Referendum Result: What it Means for Ireland
snippet.description:
About the Speech:
On 23 June 2016, the UK electorate will answer the question: “Should the United Kingdom remain a member of the European Union or leave the European Union?”. This panel discussed the implications of the result for Ireland and Northern Ireland in some key areas.


About the Speakers:

John McGrane, Director-General of The British Irish Chamber of Commerce; Blair Horan, former General Secretary of the Civil Public and Services Union (CPSU) and current member of the European Social Fund Committee; Pat Cox former President of the European Parliament; Dan O'Brien Chief Economist at the IIEA; and Brendan Halligan, IIEA Chairman.

snippet.title: UK's Markets Continue Post-Referendum Recovery!!!!
snippet.description:
The markets' recovery was boosted by Mark Carney's speech - but the British pound didn't like his words quite as much.
The UK's markets have continued to recover from the Brexit vote, with the FTSE 100 powering to its highest level for nearly a year.

The index's upward movement came as Bank of England governor Mark Carney signalled that interest rates could be lowered even further than their record 0.5% benchmark.

The FTSE 100  closed up 2.3% or 144.3 points to 6504.3, its highest level since last August and the third day of big gains for the financial markets.

The pound, however, did not like the news as much, tumbling close to the 31-year low against the US dollar that it saw just after the Brexit vote.

It fell just over a cent to 1.33 US dollars and a cent to 1.20 euros.

The FTSE 250 Index, a better measure of UK sentiment, was also sharply higher with a 1.7% rise, although it is still below its pre-Brexit level.

Tony Cross, market analyst at Trustnet Direct, said: "As if the market's behaviour in the wake of the Brexit referendum couldn't get any stranger, the FTSE 100 has now pushed out to above 6,500 for the first time since before the Chinese equity market shock last August."

But he said the twists and turns in the Conservative Party leadership contest was adding to the pound's woes.

"This has added to the unsettling of the pound again today and while this is good for stocks in the short term, the concern is that these exit negotiations need to be very carefully managed," he added.

Capital Economics economist Julian Jessop said "several plausible reasons" were behind why markets had recovered after the Brexit decision, some of which may be temporary.

"More positively, though, we think that the markets are right to recognise that Brexit, and especially some form of Brexit-lite, would not be as damaging as so many were arguing ahead of the referendum," he said in a note.

snippet.title: British pound falls 6% against U.S. dollar on early EU referendum results
snippet.description:
브렉시트 개표 시작...파운드 환율 롤러코스터
The pound plummeted after the early results in the British-EU referendum showed a potential win for "Leave."
The British currency plunged nearly six percent against the U.S. dollar, now at one-dollar forty-one cents,... after results in the northern English cities of Newcastle and Sunderland voted heavily in favor of leaving the EU, much more strongly than opinion polls had suggested.
Earlier in the evening,... when "Remain" was looking more likely, the pound hit one-dollar fifty-cents, a new high for the year.
On the market...the Japanese yen jumped one-point-four percent against the U.S. dollar.
A "Leave" vote could send shockwaves through European markets on Friday, as most analysts say investors had expected Britain to remain.

snippet.title: Headline Politics - Nicola Sturgeon Responds to Brexit Vote
snippet.description: Nicola Sturgeon, the first minister of Scotland, speaks in Edinburgh on June 24, 2016, about the outcome of the U.K. referendum on membership in the European Union. 51.9 per cent of all referendum participants voted to leave the EU but Scotland voted heavily in favour of remaining. Sturgeon discusses that discrepancy and says that a second Scottish referendum on independence from the U.K. is now very likely. In the first referendum in 2014, Scotland voted in favour of remaining in the U.K. in large part due to the threat of losing access to the EU market.

snippet.title: Trading Forex : Dampak Referendum Brexit Terhadap Trading Forex
snippet.description:
Dampak Referendum Brexit

Dampak Referendum Brexit Bagi Inggris dan Uni Eropa

Sebagaimana kita ketahui, Kamis minggu lalu, 23 Juni 2016, Inggris telah mengadakan Referendum untuk menentukan keputusan apakah Inggris memisahkan diri dari Uni Eropa atau tetap bergabung di Uni Eropa. 

Hasil resminya cukup mengejutkan saat dirilis pada jumat lalu, 24 Juni 2016 yaitu warga negara pendukung Brexit menang tipis dengan jumlah 51,9 % suara, sedangkan warga Inggris yang tetap memilih bergabung dengan uni Eropa hanya berjumlah 48,04% suara, sedangkan suara tidak sah sebesar 0,06%, terhitung dari jumlah total warga yang mengikuti Referendum sebanyak 72,2% (33.572.016 warga) dari total pemilik hak suara  sebanyak 46.501.241 warga. 

Berdasarkan hasil perhitungan suara warga yang memilih bertahan di Uni Eropa kebanyakan adalah kaum muda dan para akademisi sedangkan yang memilih keluar adalah kaum lanjut usia dan di luar akademisi.

Hasil Brexit ternyata tidaklah sesederhana yang diharapkan tapi lebih lagi banyak menimbulkan dampak yang cukup luas seperti :
 
- Perdana Menteri Inggris, David Cameroon menyatakan akan mundur dari jabatannya per bulan Oktober nanti.

- Pasar Saham Dunia sampai dengan 24 Juni 2016 kemarin alami kerugian sekitar 2,08 triliun dollar AS. Bahkan bursa saham Amerika seperti Dow Jones melemah tajam sebesar 1.5%, S&P melemah tajam sebesar 1.81% dan Nasdaq melemah tajam sebesar 2.4% pada hari ini. Bahkan S&P diprediksi akan terus melemah hingga 7% ke depannya.

- Timbulnya isu negara anggota Uni Eropa lain juga  akan mengadakan referendum untuk memisahkan diri dari uni Eropa seperti : Denmark, Polandia dan Swedia yang sebelumnya juga punya rencana keluar dari Uni Eropa bila Inggris keluar dari Uni Eropa.

- Anjloknya nilai mata uang Euro dan Poundsterling terhadap dollar AS  Pasca Brexit Jumat lalu, dimana nilai Eurusd sempat melemah 475 point pada level terendahnya 1.0909 dan GBPUSD sempat melemah 1625 point pada level terendahnya 1.3225 bahkan pelemahannya berlanjut menjadi 1731 point dari penurunan Jumat lalu hingga level 1.3119 pada hari Senin di minggu ini.

- Timbulnya kekhawatiran Uni Eropa terhadap Rusia yang akan memanfaatkan situasi jika terjadi kekacauan ekonomi Eropa setelah Brexit ini.

- Timbulnya isu perpecahan di Inggris Raya, dengan timbulnya isu yang mengusulkan agar Wilayah Irlandia Utara mengadakan referendum untuk memisahkan diri dari Inggris.

Those wanting to stay in the European Union have been boosted by a public letter from over 1,200 business leaders saying leaving the EU would harm the economy and cost Britain jobs. Most opinion polls suggest the outcome remains too close to call.
